    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-12-13T23:41:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-12-13T23:41:00-05:00" n="185"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d185">
                <head>185. Telegram 5628 From the <gloss type="from">Consulate General in
                        Dacca</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d185fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–73, <gloss
                            target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 27–14 INDIA–PAK. Secret; Flash; Exdis.
                        Repeated Flash to Islamabad and New Delhi.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d185fn2">Governor Malik informed Consul
                        General Spivack that the question of a cease-fire was being handled through
                        Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_FJS1">Farland</persName> in Islamabad and
                        that it would be unnecessary to put forward proposals from Dacca.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Dacca</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1971-12-14T04:41:00+00:00">December 14, 1971, 0441Z</date>
                </dateline>
                <pb facs="d185-01" n="1" xml:id="d185-01"/>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Possible Cease-fire in East</item>
                </list>
                <list type="references">
                    <head>Ref:</head>
                    <item>Dacca 5627</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Governor Malik has just telephoned to say that General Niazi has stated
                        that negotiations are taking place in Islamabad between central government
                        and Ambassador Farland and that there is no need for me to convey any
                        proposals.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Comment: From foregoing, there still appears to be strong difference of
                        opinion betwee Niazi and Farman with Governor oscillating feebly between.
                        Farman obviously desires to initiate some kind of action on basis his
                        appreciation of what he considers desperate local situation. Niazi, whether
                        on instructions from Islamabad or in line with his own romantic view of
                        himself as dedicated soldier, is opposed. In effect, question boils down to
                        whether <gloss target="#t_PAK1">Pak</gloss> Army in east is to be
                        sacrificed, together with uncounted thousands of civilians in East Pakistan
                        in order to retain some bargaining position in west.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHD1">Spivack</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
